The current design is carried over from TLS's minimal-overhead, unlimited-length design.  Relative to the left-hand side of the diff, you've added an octet here and imposed a 2^16 length limit.  I would counter-offer the following proposal:

```
struct {
  uint8 zero_padding[length_of_padding];
  ContentType content_type;
  select(content_type) {...}
  opaque signature<0..2^16-1>;
} MLSCiphertextContent;
```

That is, move the `content_type` inside the encrypted portion, use it as the marker byte (as in TLS), and put the padding at the front.  @raphaelrobert had made noises about the server not knowing which messages to queue if the `content_type` was opaque, but it seems like the clients do know and if the server offers scheduled and unscheduled service, can choose the appropriate type.

